-- Weber, Deutsche Telecom, RIAA: Intellectual Property
-- Victoria Slind-Flor
-- 2008-03-18T18:16:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2008-03-18/weber-deutsche-telecom-riaa-intellectual-property-update2-.html

          
          
             Weber-Stephen Products Co., the
closely held maker of Weber barbeque grills, sued two
competitors for patent infringement.  
 Weber, based in Palatine, Illinois, accused Pro-Iroda USA
Inc.'s  O-Grill  and R.H. Peterson Co.'s Grill Topper of
infringing its patent for a cooking grate with grease-control
structures. Weber sued Moreland Hills, Ohio-based  Pro-Iroda  and
 R.H. Peterson  of City of Industry, California, in two separate
suits filed in federal court in Chicago March 12.  
 In dispute is patent 7,073,429, which was issued on July
11, 2006, and which covers an assembly element in a gas-fired
grill that controls the direction of the grease generated by
cooking food on the grate.  
 Weber-Stephen applied for the patent in December 2002 and
was assisted in the application process by Chicago's  Baker &
McKenzie .  
 The complaints in both cases list all the features of the
accused products that infringe the patent. In both cases, Weber-
Stephen asked the court to find the two companies' products
infringed the patent.  
 Weber-Stephen is also seeking money damages and an order
barring the companies from selling the infringing products.  
 Baker & McKenzie's David I. Roche and Daniel A Tallitsch
represent Weber-Stephen.  
 The case against Pro-Iroda is Weber-Stephen Products Co. v.
Pro-Iroda USA Inc., 1:08-01462, U.S. District Court, northern
District of Illinois (Chicago).  
 The case against Peterson is Weber-Stephen Products Co., v.
R.H. Peterson Co., 1:08-cv-01471, U.S. District Court, Northern
District of Illinois (Chicago).  
