 Trademark  
 Haas Outdoors Sues Camo Umlimited for Trademark Infringement  
 Haas Outdoors Inc. , the first maker of camouflage clothing
to use computers to design its patterns, sued  Camo Unlimited  for
trademark infringement.  
 The company manufactures and licenses others to manufacture
camouflage clothing and accessories under the Mossy Oak
trademark. It first registered this trademark with the U.S.
patent and Trademark office in February 1989, according to the
patent office database.  
 Camo, of Blount County, Alabama, made and sold camouflage
car tags and hooded sweatshirts incorporating Haas' Mossy Oak
trademark, according to the complaint Haas filed in federal
court in Mississippi March 13.  
 Haas representatives bought two Camo sweatshirts bearing
the Mossy Oak trademark in December 2006, according to court
papers. These shirts infringe Haas' trademarks, according to the
complaint.  
 The company is asking for all profits Camo has made from
the accused projects. It claimed the infringement is deliberate,
so has asked that the money damages be tripled.  
 It's also seeking an order barring manufacture and sale of
any of Camo's infringing products.  
 Bradford Colema Ray  of Jackson, Mississippi's  Watkins
Ludlam Winter & Stennis  represents Haas.  
 The case is Haas Outdoors Inc. v. Camo Unlimited, 08-cv-
00047-SA-JAD, U.S. District Court, Northern District of
Mississippi (Eastern Division).  
 Deutsche Telecom Claims Magenta-Colored Flag Infringes  
 Deutsche Telecom AG , Europe's largest telephone company, is
not satisfied with the new shade of red adopted by a Dutch
information-technology company, the International Herald Tribune
 reported  March 16.  
 Company flags flown by Compello, based in Zwolle, the
Netherlands, triggered a complaint because the telecom company
claimed trademark rights to their magenta color, according to
the Herald Tribune.  
 The company moved to a deeper, redder color it calls ``Red
Rubin,'' but Deutsche Telecom lawyers allege it's still
infringing, according to the Herald Tribune.  
 No suit has been filed, and Compello is still adjusting its
corporate color in hopes of avoiding litigation, the Herald
Tribune reported.  
 IP Talk  
 Lawyer Disciplined for Requiring Associate to Sign Away Right  
 The Florida Supreme Court reprimanded a Miami lawyer for
requiring a newly hired associate to sign an agreement that
would have barred him from practicing IP law for a year after
leaving the firm, the Florida Bar said in a  statement  March 13.  
 Jesus Sanchelima  of  Sanchelima & Associates  was given a
public reprimand after a Feb. 14 court order, according to the
statement. He was disciplined for violating a rule of the
Florida Bar that prohibits placing restrictions on a lawyer's
practice.  
 Sanchelima, a patent lawyer and former electronics
engineer, has been in practice since 1977.  
 IP Events  
 IP Bar Group to Meet, Discuss Courts and Patent Reform  
 The American Bar Association's Section of Intellectual
Property Law will hold its annual IP law conference in
Arlington, Virginia, April 10-12.  
 Among other topics, the conference will present a program
contrasting and comparing recent patent-law holdings from the
Supreme Court of the U.S. and the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
for the Federal Circuit. That program will be led by Pamela
Banner Krupka of the Krupka Law Group of Los Angeles.  
 Representatives of the pharmaceutical and software
industries will make up part of a panel discussion on patent
reform at the conference. Robert A. Armitage, senior vice
president and general counsel of  Eli Lilly & Co. , is one of the
panelists, with the representative from the software industry
yet to be named.  
 Others on that particular program are Chief Judge Paul R.
Michel of the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, the
court that hears appeals of patent cases; and  Gerald J.
Mossinghoff , a senior counsel at Alexandria, Virginia's  Oblon,
Spivak, McClelland, Maier & Neustadt  and former patent
commissioner.  
 Registration information for the conference can be found at
the section's Web site,  www.abanet.org/intelprop .  
